The MCU clearly has inspiration from both the prime Marvel universe (616) and the Ultimate universe (1610) for some of the characters. One example is Iron Man‚Äôs nanotech armor in Infinity War reminds me a lot of Ultimate Iron Man‚Äôs armor. 
Now back to Thor, MCU Thor doesn‚Äôt wear a helmet, has facial hair and armor (especially the chest plate with the discs that glow with electricity) all very similar to Ultimate Thor. Mjolnir in the Ultimate Universe is a two handed hammer axe very similar to Stormbreaker from Avengers: Infinity War. Title: Thor - Trailer (OFFICIAL)
Comment: I still consider this film to be pretty underrated. I get some people found it boring, slow, or whatever, but I very much liked the the tone the film went for as a Shakespearean superhero drama film. It's well acted, the characters are memorable, the music brings me to tears (Patrick Doyle is such an underrated composer), the pacing moved rather smoothly, and there were nice bits of humor sprinkled in among many other things. Now does the film have flaws? Yes, but so do most movies. Personally I would have loved to see a montage of Thor and Loki's adventures over the years growing up, and a lot of scenes cut from the film should have stayed in because they actually added a lot more to the characters.

Comment: Look. "Majority" here doesn't mean majority of all the wizards in the world. It means majority of the wizards we know.
